 pos = floor(runif(1, 1, 50))

As we can see that there are some high peaks and fluctuating.

#install.packages("FBN")
library(FBN)
 
decomposed_sales = decompose(ts(sales_time, frequency = 7), "multiplicative")
plot(decomposed_sales)

Lets apply normal distribution to detect the anomalies.

random = decomposed_sales$random
min = mean(random, na.rm = T) - 4*sd(random, na.rm = T)
max = mean(random, na.rm = T) + 4*sd(random, na.rm = T)
 
plot(as.ts(as.vector(random)), ylim = c(-0.5,2.5))
abline(h=max, col="#e15f3f", lwd=2)
abline(h=min, col="#e15f3f", lwd=2)

Lets plot the anomalie.

position = data.frame(id=seq(1, length(random)), value=random)
anomalyH = position[position$value > max, ]
anomalyH = anomalyH[!is.na(anomalyH$value), ]
anomalyL = position[position$value < min, ]
anomalyL = anomalyL[!is.na(anomalyL$value), ]
anomaly = data.frame(id=c(anomalyH$id, anomalyL$id),
 value=c(anomalyH$value, anomalyL$value))
anomaly = anomaly[!is.na(anomaly$value), ]
 
plot(as.ts(sales_time))
real = data.frame(id=seq(1, length(sales_time)), value=sales_time)
realAnomaly = real[anomaly$id, ]
points(x = realAnomaly$id, y =realAnomaly$value, col="#e15f3f")

From the above plot we have seen that there are so many sales in between starting range. Lets try moving average decomposition

#install.packages("forecast")
library(forecast)
## Warning: package 'forecast' was built under R version 3.5.3
library(stats)
 
trend = runmed(sales_time, 7)
plot(as.ts(trend))

detrend = sales_time / as.vector(trend)
m = t(matrix(data = detrend, nrow = 7))
## Warning in matrix(data = detrend, nrow = 7): data length [2823] is not a
## sub-multiple or multiple of the number of rows [7]
seasonal = colMeans(m, na.rm = T)
random = sales_time / (trend * seasonal)
## Warning in trend * seasonal: longer object length is not a multiple of
## shorter object length
rm_random = runmed(random[!is.na(random)], 3)
 
min = mean(rm_random, na.rm = T) - 4*sd(rm_random, na.rm = T)
max = mean(rm_random, na.rm = T) + 4*sd(rm_random, na.rm = T)
plot(as.ts(random))
abline(h=max, col="#e15f3f", lwd=2)
abline(h=min, col="#e15f3f", lwd=2)

From the above two plots we can see that most the anomalies are in starting time. So lets subset the anomaly of that time and lets do the root cause analysis for that.

ts_subset <- window(sales_time, end = c(2003),frequency = 0.2)
